In [[linguistics]], the '''donor principle''' refers primarily to the observance of the original spelling of a [[loanword]] from the original ("donor") language. This principle applies in particular to the standardization in the receiver language of [[exonym]]s when they are used in publications.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.eurogeographics.org/sites/default/files/080205_D5.1_Exonyms%20guidelines%20synopsis.pdf|title= Exonyms guidelines synopsis |date= |website= |publisher= EuroGeoNames|access-date= |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author1=Peter Jordan |author2=Milan Orožen Adamič |author3=Paul Woodman |title= Exonyms and the International Standardisation of Geographical Names |url= https://books.google.nl/books?id=NVReAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA11&lpg=PA11&dq=%22exonym%22+%22donor+principle%22&source=bl&ots=xVfZqoTJU5&sig=rdggekWiaLi1VCHjqyswhpCxhN8&hl=nl&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjB-sL0-_LPAhUoDcAKHW02Br0Q6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=%22exonym%22%20%22donor%20principle%22&f=false|location= |publisher= |page= 11|date= 2007|isbn=}}</ref>
The term donor principle is sometimes also used for the particular spelling of names of specific products, brands, institutions etc. chosen by their owner, founder, designer, etc., when it clashes with the official spelling rules.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ru.nl/publish/pages/546019/nunnenneijtrecenthistory3.doc |title=The recent history of Dutch orthography (II). Problems solved and created by the 2005 reform |date= |website=www.ru.nl |publisher=Dutch Department, Radboud University, Nijmegen |access-date= |quote= }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> This often pertains to the use of [[capital letter]]s. (e.g. ''[[YouTube]]''), for example.
